# GraphQL Cursor Rules

## Schema Design
- Use descriptive type names: `User`, `CreateUserInput`, `UserConnection`
- Use `input` types for mutations, object types for queries
- Use `enum` for fixed sets of values
- Implement Relay-style pagination: `Connection`, `Edge`, `PageInfo`
- Use interfaces for shared fields across types

## Resolvers
- Keep resolvers thin — delegate to service/data layer
- Use DataLoader for batching and caching (prevent N+1)
- Return typed errors in the response, not just throwing
- Implement field-level resolvers only when needed

## Mutations
- Name mutations as verb+noun: `createUser`, `updateArticle`, `deleteComment`
- Return the mutated object in the response
- Use input validation before processing
- Implement optimistic responses on the client

## Security
- Implement authentication in context, not resolvers
- Use field-level authorization with directives or middleware
- Limit query depth and complexity to prevent abuse
- Disable introspection in production

## Performance
- Use DataLoader for all relationship fields
- Implement query complexity analysis
- Use persisted queries for trusted clients
- Cache frequently accessed data at the resolver level
